{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":14049,"record_hash":"sha256:811c78f8996f33213537b35e78f728d7fa78d2e1a488b18912146d8d65b8d2ae","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:33:09.140Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Delete File: [REDACTED:entropy].md\n*** Add File: [REDACTED:entropy].md\n+# GitMeta Data Model\n+\n+## Principles\n+\n+- Store durable agent sessions on the `project` target by default.\n+- Use shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys for GitButler agentlog data.\n+- Do not use `meta:local:*` for the main session records; GitMeta treats local\n+  keys as never serialized.\n+- Redact all copied transcript strings before writing.\n+- Keep branch, pull request, change, and commit links as future references to\n+  durable project sessions, not owners of session data.\n+- Do not write standard `agent:*` keys until there is an interoperability or\n+  publication contract.\n+- Do not call GitMeta serialize, push, fetch, or sync in the POC.\n+\n+GitMeta stores metadata as `(target, key, value)` tuples. Supported target types\n+include `commit`, `change-id`, `branch`, `path`, and `project`. Keys are\n+namespace-like strings split on `:`, and list values are append-friendly logs.\n+\n+## Standard Agent Keys\n+\n+GitMeta recommends keys such as:\n+\n+```text\n+agent:provider\n+agent:model\n+agent:session-id\n+agent:prompt\n+agent:summary\n+agent:transcript\n+```\n+\n+These are likely future interoperability keys, but they are not first-POC\n+storage. The POC writes GitButler-owned keys only.\n+\n+## POC Storage Model\n+\n+For the first implementation, write to `project` unless `--target` is explicit.\n+\n+Session index:\n+\n+```text\n+gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n+```\n+\n+Durable session prefix:\n+\n+```text\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n+```\n+\n+Session-level keys:\n+\n+```text\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:schema = gitbutler.agent-session.v1\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:updated-at = <capture timestamp>\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:sources = set<source-key>\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:record-hashes = set<sha256:record>\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript = list<TranscriptEnvelope JSON>\n+```\n+\n+Source-level keys:\n+\n+```text\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:agent\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:provider\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:model\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:tool-version\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:provider-session-key\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:source-name\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:source-size\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:source-sha256\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:last-record-index\n+gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:source:<source-key>:captured-at\n+```\n+\n+Do not store full transcript paths, cwd, git branch names, or raw provider\n+session ids. `source-name` is basename only. `provider-session-key` is hashed.\n+\n+## Session and Source Keys\n+\n+Provider session ids are opaque and may contain private identifiers. Do not put\n+the raw provider session id in GitMeta keys or scalar values.\n+\n+For this POC, derive `session-key` as:\n+\n+```text\n+sha256(agent + NUL + provider-session-id)\n+```\n+\n+If no provider session id exists, derive it from:\n+\n+```text\n+sha256(agent + NUL + canonical-transcript-path-bytes)\n+```\n+\n+`source-key` identifies the captured source file. The POC derives it from the\n+agent plus canonical transcript path bytes. This lets one durable provider\n+session later contain multiple source entries without overwriting source\n+metadata.\n+\n+## Transcript Envelope\n+\n+Keep one ordered `:transcript` list per durable GitButler session. Each list item\n+is one redacted JSON envelope with only per-record data:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+\t\"schema\": \"gitbutler.agent-transcript.v1\",\n+\t\"source_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n+\t\"record_index\": 0,\n+\t\"record_hash\": \"sha256:...\",\n+\t\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-07T09:08:43.427Z\",\n+\t\"event_kind\": \"response_item\",\n+\t\"event_category\": \"message\",\n+\t\"role\": \"assistant\",\n+\t\"content_text\": \"redacted normalized text when easy to extract\",\n+\t\"tool_name\": null,\n+\t\"source_record\": {}\n+}\n+```\n+\n+`content_text` is the normalized conversation message body when it is obvious to\n+extract. `tool_name` is only copied from obvious Codex or Claude fields.\n+\n+Omit repeated session/source metadata from each envelope. Use `source_key` to\n+join an envelope back to source metadata. Also omit cwd, git branch, provider\n+session ids, message ids, parent ids, turn ids, and redaction counters from\n+top-level envelope fields.\n+\n+`event_category` is one of:\n+\n+```text\n+session\n+context\n+message\n+tool\n+other\n+```\n+\n+Preserve the parsed provider record in redacted `source_record` so future\n+normalizers can improve without losing provenance. Redaction changes stored\n+string values, not JSON object keys. Record hashes and dedupe use the original\n+trimmed JSONL bytes.\n+\n+## Deduplication\n+\n+Use stable record hashes:\n+\n+```text\n+sha256(trimmed raw JSONL line bytes)\n+```\n+\n+The session-level `record-hashes` set tracks metadata dedupe. Transcript append\n+dedupe is rebuilt from the stored envelope list by reading each envelope's\n+`record_hash`. This keeps transcript backfill possible if the list is missing\n+while the record hash set still exists.\n+\n+Repeat capture of the same session should:\n+\n+- write no duplicate transcript envelopes\n+- append only newly observed records when a transcript grows\n+- keep source provenance keys up to date once per successful capture\n+\n+## Future Association Model\n+\n+Do not attach transcript data directly to branches, commits, changes, or pull\n+requests in the POC. The project session is the durable object.\n+\n+Later, when GitButler has an explicit target, write relationship references:\n+\n+```text\n+<branch/change/commit target>\n+  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n+```\n+\n+This supports:\n+\n+- one session contributing to multiple branches or pull requests\n+- multiple sessions contributing to one branch or pull request\n+- sessions that exist before any code or branch association\n+\n+See [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md) for the product scenarios this\n+supports.\n+\n+## Serialization\n+\n+The POC does not call GitMeta serialize, push, fetch, or sync. It writes\n+shareable-ready keys but leaves remote exchange for a later integration with\n+explicit privacy and product behavior.\n+\n+## Redaction\n+\n+All stored agentlog values copied from transcripts are redacted before writing.\n+The POC uses a small guard for sensitive field names, high-entropy strings,\n+UUID-shaped values, and random-looking long hex strings. This is intentionally\n+not a complete secret scanner; it is a pragmatic safety net for the first data\n+shape.\n+\n+Future work may add repository settings, user confirmation, stronger scanners,\n+or destination-specific publication filters before metadata is exchanged.\n+\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:33:09.140Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}